      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I'll try to keep the goblin analogies to a minimum. Wind shear and jet stream interaction can lead to clear air turbulence due to the complex interactions between atmospheric flows.\n\nWind shear occurs when there is a significant change in wind speed or direction with height, typically within a few hundred meters. This can be caused by various factors, such as the interaction with terrain features, the presence of mountains or hills, or the influence of weather systems like fronts or low-pressure systems.\n\nThe jet stream, a fast-moving band of air in the upper atmosphere, can interact with wind shear in several ways. When the jet stream encounters a region of wind shear, it can cause the air to be stretched and compressed, leading to the formation of turbulence. This is because the jet stream is typically a narrow, high-speed flow, while the wind shear is a more complex, three-dimensional flow.\n\nThe interaction between the jet stream and wind shear can be described using the concept of vorticity, which is a measure of the rotation of a fluid. When the jet stream encounters wind shear, it can create vortices, or rotating air masses, that can lead to the formation of turbulence. These vortices can be thought of as \"goblin whirlp",
